<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-089 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Clashes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Clashes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0705024994 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0104 GMT 7 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0705024994 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Caracas, 6 May (NOTIMEX) -- A demonstration by 
students who were protesting the death of one of their 
classmates yesterday overshadowed the nine-hour meeting held by 
the presidents of Venezuela and Colombia. 
  Barely two blocks away from Miraflores presidential palace, 
Fermin Toro High School students who were holding a vigil for 
slain student German Sotillo, whom police shot to death, became 
too excited and clashed with the public security forces. 
  Presidents Cesar Gaviria and Rafael Caldera had to meet 
exclusively at Miraflores and not at the Foreign Ministry, where 
the signing of a joint document had been scheduled. 
  Even though the authorities were able to momentarily 
dissuade 
the demonstrators, who were protesting because bus drivers were 
not accepting preferential fares for students, clashes became 
more intense during the afternoon, when Sotillo was buried. 
  Following the funeral at a cemetery in this capital attended 
by approximately 5,000 high school students and people from 
various social organizations, violence returned to the streets 
of downtown Caracas, but there were no reports of casualties. 
  The Judicial Technical Police, in a last-minute report, 
stated the officer who fired the shots that killed Sotillo and 
wounded three other students confessed and was immediately 
arrested so that homicide charges would be brought against him. 
However, that announcement was unable to calm the angry 
students, whose protests spread to at least three other high 
schools in this capital. 
  In view of the prevailing tension and following the 
transportation sector's announcement to increase general bus 
fares, the students, including university students, announced 
that more protests were planned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56732 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat089_t_94004" </HT>


