<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Castro, 15 Leaders Meet To Ratify Resolution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Castro, 15 Leaders Meet To Ratify Resolution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0705000694 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0705000694 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This afternoon in Barbados, Cuban President Fidel 
Castro stated that nongovernmental organizations [NGO's] have 
become a powerful force in international politics. Fidel is 
participating in the First International Small Island Nations 
Conference on Sustainable Development, and met in Bridgetown 
with NGO representatives from the Caribbean and Mediterranean 
Seas, and the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans. At the beginning of 
the colloquy, (Jean Preanch), spokeswoman for the Caribbean 
organizations, stressed the support to Cuba that was 
demonstrated in the recently concluded NGO summit, which 
rejected the U.S. blockade against Cuba. 
  Fidel applauded the manifestations of support and solidarity 
and received tremendous applause from the crowd when he stated: 
We feel among you that we are among friends, brothers. This is 
why I leave Barbados and this conference very happy. 
  In his closing statements, Castro stressed the importance of 
the Barbados summit for organizing an action strategy to defend 
the islands from serious, looming problems such as pollution, 
radioactive wastes, and climate changes. 
  This afternoon, Fidel met behind close doors with the other 
15 heads of state in attendance to ratify the final version of 
the Barbados Resolution and the action plan that will close the 
meeting. 

</TEXT>

