<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0505212694 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>
<F P=103> PY0505212694 </F>
<F P=104>  -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 5 May. 
  According to information published by the DIARIO OFICIAL, 
Central Bank profits reached $20.1 billion in 1993. According 
to Getulio Vargas Foundation economist Rubens Cysne, real 
profits amount to $4 billion, as the so-called inflationary tax 
of $16 billion, which the productive sector transfers to the 
banks because of inflation, must be deducted from the original 
figure. (Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 2 May 94 
p 11) 
  After registering record sales in March, when 118,000 units 
were sold, the Brazilian automobile industry registered a 25 
percent drop in April, when 94,000 vehicles were sold. This 
number includes imported cars. In April, Volkswagen sold 33,000 
units, Fiat 25,000, General Motors 21,000, and Ford 13,000. 
(Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 4 May 94 
Business and Finance Section p 1) 

</TEXT>

