<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Views Reducing Deficit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Finance Minister Views Reducing Deficit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0805032194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1420 GMT 5 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0805032194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 5 May (PL) -- The positive signs following 
implementation of the Cuban budget during the first months of 
the year will make possible a reduction of the current deficit, 
which amounts to 1 billion pesos (the official exchange rate is 
one peso per dollar), should these indicators remain the same. 
This statement was included in an analysis Finance and Prices 
Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez presented to the recent meeting of 
the presidents of the Provincial Administration Councils 
[Consejos de Administracion Provinciales], the local 
authorities' administrative institutions. 
  Rodriguez told the Chamber of Representatives, which opened 
its session in this city, efforts at the provincial levels are 
being made to contribute to the reduction of the national 
deficit, which was estimated at 4.2 billion pesos in late 1993. 
  The minister said this encouraging sign is based on the 
implementation of the budget during the first part of the year. 
He added the budget includes more revenues, less expenditures, 
and a 6.1-percent reduction in the estimated budget deficit. 
  Rodriguez also praised the aggressive efforts by the 
provincial and national cities regarding collections and 
payments because these efforts allowed for a reduction of 440 
million pesos in accounts payable of the first quarter of 1994. 
  The finance and prices minister said [words indistinct] to 
prevent past financial irregularities, for instance, the 
noncollection of debts, from happening again in the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

