<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rejects U.S. Influence in Administration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rejects U.S. Influence in Administration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005042994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0230 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1005042994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with President-elect Ernesto Perez Balladares by </F>
correspondent Veronica Duran; place and date not given; from the 
"CMI Newscast" -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Perez Balladares] Torrijos always said we had two 
countries with which we sleep every day: Colombia and Costa 
Rica. Of course, they are our neighbors, and we want to have 
very close, cordial, and helpful relations with them. 
  [Duran] What will be your position vis-a-vis the United 
States? 
  [Perez Balladares] One of respect. I believe the 
Torrijos-Carter Treaties are our best references. We, as well 
as the United States, know that respect is the best way to 
ensure good relations and that the implementation of and 
compliance with those treaties are fundamental to positive 
relations between our countries. 
  [Duran] Is it true that Panama is a U.S. puppet? 
  [Perez Balladares] No, God forbid. We, however, do have many 
joint interests in the Panama Canal enterprise. Those interests 
will continue, but with the difference that the Canal will now 
be managed entirely by Panamanians. No, Panama is not a U.S. 
puppet. 
  [Duran] Does the United States influence the government in 
any way? 
  [Perez Balladares] The current government? 
  [Duran] Yes. 
  [Perez Balladares] Well, you will have to ask the president 
that question. In my administration, there will be a great deal 
of respect and consideration, but no influence. 
  [Duran] Do you see any political future for [presidential 
candidate Ruben] Blades? 
  [Perez Balladares] I believe that, in addition to youth, 
some 
political experience is required, and Ruben, who is my friend 
and whose music I enjoy, does not have it. I, of course, offer 
him the opportunity to acquire this experience during my 
government. 

</TEXT>

