<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cavallo Downplays Deficit, Defends Job Creation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cavallo Downplays Deficit, Defends Job Creation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0905135794 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2356 GMT 6 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY0905135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Buenos Aires, 6 May (NA) -- Economy Minister 
Domingo Cavallo stated on 6 May that the trade deficit "does not 
constitute a problem" because it is caused by the importation of 
capital goods, which produce "more investments." The economy 
minister stressed: "The increase in imports does not constitute 
a problem if it helps to increase our productive capacity." 
  Cavallo conceded that the unemployment number is 
"worrisome," 
while snapping out that "1.5 million new jobs have been created 
over the last four years." He argued: "During October 1989, 
there were 11.5 million people employed. This figure increased 
to 12.5 million in October 1993 while in the last six years it 
had grown by only 600,000." [passage omitted] 
  The minister said one should wonder "why more new jobs are 
not being created." He said many small- and medium-scale 
entrepreneurs "are afraid of the law on accidents on the 
shop-floor and current labor laws." 
  This prompted him to reiterate his request for the enactment 
of the Labor Flexibility Law because "we must have more 
realistic labor laws, at least for the Pymes [small- and 
medium-scale enterprises]." 
  To conclude, Cavallo pointed out that over the last three 
years the country has grown "25 percent," which means Argentina 
"has recorded the third largest growth rate in the world." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

