Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lula Outlines Foreign Policy, State Role in Economy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lula Outlines Foreign Policy, State Role in Economy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0905230194 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 7 
May 94 p A7 </F>

<F P=103> PY0905230194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Lucia Helena Gazzola] </F>
  [Excerpt] On 6 May, PT [Workers Party] presidential 
candidate Luis Inacio Lula da Silva said that if he is elected, 
his foreign policy would promote a debate on a "new 
international political and economic order" and would seek to 
establish "sound" ties with countries that have large consumer 
markets and that are not aligned with economic blocs. In 
addition to Mercosur [Common Market of the South] countries, he 
mentioned South Africa, India, China, and Russia. 
  Lula made it clear that he does not intend to attach 
priority 
to traditional Brazilian partners: "Over the past five 
centuries Brazil has had trade relations with practically Europe 
and the United States alone, which have now closed themselves 
off into large blocs." He said his foreign policy would be 
"active, with as much traveling as possible, to make Brazil 
approach those countries and show the governments of rich 
countries the problems and the development model that Brazil 
wants to implement." 
  Lula spoke shortly before dedicating the headquarters of his 
campaign's central committee on Angelica Avenue, in downtown Sao 
Paulo, on the eve of his departure for the United States. He 
will leave today on a five-day visit during which he will meet 
with U.S. officials, businessmen, and official organizations. 
  Lula also referred to the type of "strong state" that he 
wants to build in Brazil: "It will not be a state that will 
meddle with the economy, but a strong state that will promote a 
good taxation policy and increase revenues and investment to 
resolve the problems of starvation and misery in the country," 
he explained. He added that in his government, "the sectors 
that are not strategic" for national sovereignty might be 
transferred to the private sector, yet he said that instead of 
thinking about the privatization of existing hydroelectric 
plants or highways, entrepreneurs should try to build what 
Brazil still needs to promote its development. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

