<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Health Strike Ends; Hospitals Resume Services </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Health Strike Ends; Hospitals Resume Services </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1005011894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1522 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1005011894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 6 May (EFE) -- State hospital services 
returned to normal today following the 72-hour national strike. 
The 55,000 mobilized health workers, however, threatened to 
stage an indefinite strike if their salary demands are not met. 
  The health minister said that only 30 percent of all health 
workers participated in the strike. Workers' leaders, however, 
claimed that the percentage of participating strikers was 
larger. Services at hospital outpatient clinics dropped 
substantially during the three-day strike. 
  Workers rejected the recent salary increase granted by the 
government, characterizing it as "miserable." Health Minister 
Jaime Freundt-Thurne said the state does not have any money for 
new salary increases. 
  Health workers earn an average salary of less than $150 per 
month. They criticized the minister for refusing to negotiate 
with their union, and threatened to stage an indefinite strike. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

