<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Transportation Strike Leaves Caracas `Paralyzed' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Transportation Strike Leaves Caracas `Paralyzed' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0905154294 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 
9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0905154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "180 Minutes of News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The transportation strike is in effect throughout 
the metropolitan areas of Caracas, Sucre District, and Carabobo 
State. In terms of Caracas, the city is paralyzed. The strike 
was called because the government owes transportation workers 
student fare subsidies but has failed to pay, despite an earlier 
announcement that the payments will be made. 
  Passenger buses and cabs shut their engines off last night. 
The government has warned it will crack down on any public 
disorder. Interior Minister Ramon Escovar Salom addressed the 
nation last night and called on students not to be influenced by 
the professional agitators taking advantage of the 
transportation strike. The government, through the Interior 
Ministry, called today's transportation strike illegal and urged 
reflection on the situation. The minister also said the 
transportation strike is unfounded. He said the government has 
the funds to pay the subsidy on preferential student bus fares, 
which is the reason behind the call for the strike. 
  [Begin Escovar recording] A strike like this affects the 
poorer sectors of the population and harms the general interest 
of the community. Therefore, it is an affront against the 
nation's basic interests, which the government is obliged to 
defend as established by the Constitution and the law. [end 
recording] 
  Minister Escovar Salom reminded the transportation workers 
that routes and permits are granted by the government and must 
be used to serve the public and not personal interest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

