<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army's Strategic Plan Focuses on Postwar Era </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Army's Strategic Plan Focuses on Postwar Era </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005153694 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 7 May 94 
p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PA1005153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Colonel Morris Eugenio de Leon, chief of the 
Information and Press Department of the Army (DIDE), says the 
Armed Forces are preparing for a postwar era and for a revision 
of goals, according to a strategic modernization and 
reorganization plan. 
  The Armed Forces will no longer devote their time solely to 
wiping out guerrillas. Now, they will also participate in 
social activities. According to De Leon, a close look at the 
situation shows that individual rights must be respected. 
  An example of the Army's new duties is its decision to 
cooperate with the arrival of 521 refugee families from Mexico. 
As of 13 May, the Guatemalan Air Force will begin making 18 
flights in Araba airplanes to transport the belongings of the 
refugees, who will be returning to Mayalan, Quiche, where they 
will attempt to live despite the continuing presence of 
guerrillas in the area. 
  The return of the refugees, De Leon added, is part of the 
aforementioned program, the deadline for which is the year 2003. 
The plan does not include a reduction in the Armed Forces High 
Command because its goal is to control future military 
promotions to prevent saturation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

