<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Mulino To Join Opposition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Mulino To Join Opposition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005222794 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 10 May 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PA1005222794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Otero] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Jose Raul Mulino said yesterday 
that as soon as his work in the current government is completed, 
he will join the political opposition of his country to monitor, 
together with the group led by Ruben Dario Carles, the 
Democratic Revolutionary Party [PRD]. 
  Mulino said that he, as a private citizen, supported the 
political option Carles represented during these elections, 
because he believes it was the best, and he said he respects the 
people's decision and accepts defeat. 
  Mulino said: "I am one of Carles' friends. We accept 
defeat, but we will continue our struggle and political 
militancy to monitor the PRD." 
  Mulino formed part of the civic groups that struggled 
against 
militarism without being part of any party, although now he 
announced "he will become a member of one very soon," but he did 
not specify of which party. 
  Mulino said he will conclude his work at the Foreign 
Ministry 
on 1 September, when he will then become a part of his country's 
opposition. 
  Mulino praised President Guillermo Endara, saying he made 
possible free and honest elections that will go down in history 
as an example for future generations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

