2300 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1105012594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ciro Ortega; from the "RPC Television News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Panamanian Foreign Minister Jose Raul Mulino has 
said the placet for the new U.S. ambassador to Panama will be 
issued this week. 
  The foreign minister has said the advancement of diplomatic 
relations with the United States is vital for the transition 
period that will lead to the handing over of the Panama Canal 
during the year 2000. 
  Mulino has said the placet will be given to the U.S. 
ambassador to Panama who will replace Deane Hinton, most likely 
Robert Pastor. 
  [Begin recording] [Mulino] I think it is most important to 
maintain close relations with the United States during the 
coming five-year period. I think President-elect Perez 
Balladares will need that. This is a fundamental task. Once 
they assume the government, they will see the task involving the 
canal issue is huge and requires much tending; because of this, 
President Endara and I will evaluate this appointment on 12 May. 
  [Ortega] How is the transition for the Foreign Ministry to 
the next government progressing? 
  [Mulino] Yesterday, I personally called my successor, my 
great and good friend Gabriel Lewis Galindo, who has confirmed 
to me he will be the next foreign minister, to put my working 
team, our experience, and our cooperation at his disposal so 
that when he takes over the Foreign Ministry on 2 September he 
may routinely go to work ignoring nothing about the 
international negotiations we are conducting or the integration 
processes in which we are engaged with Colombia and Central 
America. 
  I will also give him certain recommendations, in writing, on 
the canal issue and on the modernization the Foreign Ministry 
requires, modernization we have been unable to make due to 
economic limitations. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

