<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005235994 </F>
<F P=103> PA1005235994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 10 May. 
  The Comptroller General's Office announced in a communique 
that on 5 May policemen will receive $1.477 in wage increases, 
which will be retroactive to 1 January. (Panama City EL SIGLO in 
Spanish 5 May 94 p 60) 
  In 1993, the Colon Free Zone's overall commercial activities 
totaled $8.837.3 billion and generated approximately 9 percent 
of the GNP. Imports during the first quarter of 1994 have 
totaled $1.070.8 billion, compared to $790.2 million during the 
same period in 1993, an increase of $280.6 million. Meanwhile, 
first-quarter reexport figures totaled $1.161.3 billion in 1993 
and have increased to $1.283 billion this year. Reexports 
totaled $5.110 billion in 1993, an increase of 6 percent over 
the 1992 figures. Total imports in 1993 were $4.493 billion. 
(Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 6 May 94 p B-1) 
  The Panamanian Government will exchange bonds for $452 
million with Japanese and European financial markets. This 
transaction will be carried out soon in London. Planning 
Minister Delia Cardenas announced that the Panamanian Government 
is working on the final adjustments to renegotiate approximately 
$452 million owed to Japanese and European markets. With regard 
to the commercial debt, which totals $3.2 billion, Minister 
Cardenas said renegotiations are under way, counterproposals 
have been received, and the various alternatives are being 
studied. (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 
GMT 5 May 94) 

</TEXT>

