<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Drug Traffickers Vie for Control of Tijuana </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Drug Traffickers Vie for Control of Tijuana </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1105021694 Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 9 May 94 pp 1, 
12 </F>

<F P=103> PA1105021694 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City UNOMASUNO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Francisco Gomez and Lorenzo Garibay] </F>
  [Text] Tijuana, Baja California, 8 May -- Given its 
geographic location, its almost 40 km of common border with the 
United States' richest state, and its economic potential, this 
city has been one of the areas most contested by drug gangs and 
cartels operating in Mexico. This is particularly true of the 
those led by the Arellano Felix brothers and by Hector Palma 
Salazar, alias El Guero Palma. 
  The war among drug trafficking mafias has left behind a wake 
of death and violence. In the past two years, more than 50 
"executions" have taken place involving the death of people 
linked to these two gangs that are vying for control of this 
area, which is strategic for drug trafficking. 
  Tijuana, which is a natural stepping stone to the world's 
largest drug consuming market, has been known for its large 
numbers of drug seizures. In the past 16 months in this area, 
approximately 65,500 kg of marijuana and 16,316 kg of cocaine as 
well as 10 kg of heroin have been seized, demonstrating that 
this is a place favored by drug traffickers, according to the 
Attorney General's Office. 
  The streets in this city have been the scene of drug 
trafficking gang rivalries and of police complicity with these 
gangs as well as an increase in drug abuse among the community, 
particularly among youths. 
  So far this year, five deaths have been attributed to the 
drug trafficking groups. Of these deaths, the murder of 
Alejandro Castaneda Andre, commander of the special group of the 
Judicial Federal Police [PFJ], and the 28 April murder of 
Federico Benitez Lopez, director of Municipal Public Security 
and of his driver Ramon Alerid Cardenas, stand out. In this 
last case, no one has been arrested, and there are no leads. In 
the Castaneda Andrade case, however, a state judicial police 
officer, who was in the company of a group of drug traffickers, 
and a "godmother" were arrested. Nevertheless, what is most 
remarkable is that legal action was taken against Sergio Ortiz 
Lara, the state's deputy prosecutor, for helping in the escape 
of members of the Arellano Felix gangs. 
  According to an investigation conducted by the National Poll 
on drug use in Baja California and Tijuana, in particular, the 
community is becoming a large consumer market, particularly for 
drugs such as cocaine and crack. The study results indicate that 
the majority of the youths polled in junior high and high 
schools started abusing drugs before they were 15. 
  The drug cartels' struggle to impose their control on this 
area has given way to the so-called "executions," which, in the 
last 24 months, have taken as victims a state judicial police 
agent; Wenceslao Berinstain Avila, a former Attorney General's 
Office agent; Pedro Rodriguez Moreno, a customs agent; Israel 
Alvarado Acosta and an associate; and Jose Luis Stavinsky, son 
of a well-know Tijuana businessman, in addition to many other 
victims. The majority of these cases remain unpunished. 
  The drug cartels' struggle for this city and other important 
sites for drug trafficking activities came out in the open a 
year ago in Guadalajara, Jalisco, when Cardinal Juan Jesus 
Posada Ocampo and six other individuals were murdered. The 
incident took place during a confrontation at the Guadalajara 
airport among groups led by the Arellano Felix brothers; Joaquin 
Guzman Loera, alias El Chapo Guzman; and El Guero Palma. 
Previously a confrontation had taken place between them at the 
disco Christine de Puerto Vallarta. 
  The Arellano Felix brothers, Ramon, Benjamin, and Javier, 
are the ones who have controlled this activity in Tijuana in the 
past few years, after they inherited control from their uncle 
Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo. Felix Gallardo during his time and 
up until his incarceration at the high security penitentiary in 
Almoloya, Juarez, was considered the capo of Mexico's largest 
drug trafficking ring. 
  Arellano Felix's power and influence became obvious when 35 
safe houses, a farm, and an industrial factory were seized. An 
unfinished tunnel was uncovered in the factory. This tunnel was 
to connect Tijuana with San Diego to smuggle drugs into the 
United States. 
  Recently the PGR sold off properties belonging to this gang 
consisting of 12 furniture lots, stuffed animals, vintage wines, 
paintings and sculptures of well-known artists, and other 
ostentatious articles. The starting bidding price was 134,642 
pesos. Two days before, 11 homes that had been seized were put 
on public auction, however, only one was sold, the price of 
which is unknown. The company in charge of carrying out this 
operation was Avaluos Integrales S.A. de CV, contracted by the 
PGR itself. 
  Up until now, the Arrellano Felix brothers remain at large 
with the exception of Francisco Javier Arellano Felix, who was 
arrested by the PJF in Tijuana in December. He was transferred 
to the Almoloya high security jail in Juarez where his staunch 
rival, Joaquin Guzman, alias El Chapo Guzman, has been since 
June. El Chapo Guzman was arrested in Guatemala and turned over 
to the Mexican authorities. 
  The last time any news was heard about the Arellano Felix 
gang was on 3 March during the shoot out in which Alexandro 
Castaneda Andrade, commander of the special group of the PFJ in 
that city, was killed. Andrade had located the site where 
Javier Arellano Felix, alias El Tigrillo, and his lieutenant 
Ismael Higuera Guerrero, alias El Mayel, were hiding. He was 
killed, however, during the confrontation when he attempted to 
arrest them. The case still has not been totally cleared up, 
but, according to versions of the PRG itself, El Tigrillo and El 
Mayel had already been arrested but were released by state 
police agents, allegedly by deputy prosecutor Sergio Ortiz Lara 
himself. Ortiz Lara is currently under arrest for his alleged 
responsibility in this case. 
  The most recent victim here of the drug trafficking groups 
was Federico Benitez Lopez, director of Municipal Security 
Police, and his driver Alarid Cardenas, who were murdered 10 
days ago on the highway in La Mesa. Benitez Lopez became known 
for confiscating weapons and marijuana in that city. 
  Benitez Lopez held that post for five months, when the drug 
trafficking phenomena was to be attacked in a joint action on 
three government levels. Nevertheless, the plans failed due to 
the rivalries among the different police corps and the 
corruption spread by the distribution of dollars by organized 
crime. 
  The large drug cargoes that reach this border have resulted 
in a peculiar phenomena: San Diego California drug addicts come 
to exchange weapons for drugs. This was reported by David Rubi, 
chief of the Tactic Group, who affirmed that weekly a weapon 
known as a goat's horn [cuerno de chivo] is found in the hands 
of gang members in this city's poor neighborhoods. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-56931 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat091_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-091 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1005195994 </F>
<F P=103> PA1005195994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 10 May. 
  The Mexican mining industry has suffered a 12 percent drop 
in 
production over the past four years, according to the Trade 
Union of Miners. The union also reported that 30,000 workers 
have been laid off during this period. (Mexico City XEW 
Television Network in Spanish 0435 GMT 4 May 94) 
  The price of domestic raw materials rose 3.1 percent in the 
first quarter of 1994, according to an EL FINANCIERO study based 
on figures from the Bank of Mexico. The newspaper's analysts 
point out that this rate of inflation was below the inflation 
rate recorded by raw materials on the international market, 
which rose 8.6 percent in the same period. Nevertheless, the 
study points out that in 1990-93, Mexican consumer prices rose 
annually at 26.7, 22.7, 15.5, and 9.8 percent, while domestic 
raw materials rose only 23.6, 8.3, 5.7, and 1.7 percent, 
respectively. The difference lies in the price of imported 
materials, which are usually higher. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO 
in Spanish 5 May 94 p 3A) 
  Higher inflation and less economic growth are now the 
government's projections for 1994. Following the murder of 
presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio and the events 
surrounding the investigation and the election process, the 
government has adjusted the targets in its economic plan. Now, 
inflation is expected to reach 7-8 percent, and GNP growth has 
been revised downward and is expected to range between 1.5 and 2 
percent. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 5 May 94 p 24) 
  Unemployment in the 37 largest metropolitan areas rose to 
3.8 
percent in January, the highest January figure since 1992 and 
the third highest within the past 24 months. The National 
Institute of Statistics, Geography, and Information (INEGI) 
reported that 1.286 million people are out of work. Some 
180,000 of these people are teens and young adults with no 
previous job experience, who were forced into the labor market 
and have not yet found work. INEGI monitors this figure on a 
weekly basis. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 5 May 94 pp 
60, 48) 
  An EL FINANCIERO study based on INEGI statistics indicates 
that the number of new jobs offered during the first quarter of 
1994 showed a negligible increase of 0.1 percent. Only 11,000 
new jobs were made available, which means that the government 
will reach its goal of 500,000 new jobs a year over a four-year 
period. The report concludes by saying the private sector has 
reported layoffs and closures in most major areas of production, 
which in turn makes it poor source of new jobs. (Mexico City EL 
FINANCIERO in Spanish 6 May 94 p 3A) 
  The Confederation of National Chambers of Commerce 
(Concanaco) has reported that the private sector's contribution 
to the nation's GNP dropped 1.2 percent in 1993. This is the 
largest fall since 1986. According to a Concanaco study, this 
had a negative effect on jobs and sales. The report projects, 
however, that there will be some recovery during the first 
quarter of 1994, although this recovery will be modest. (Mexico 
City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 6 May 94 p 28) 
  The Mexican Secretariat of Agriculture and Hydraulic 
Resources (SARH) has reported that the agricultural trade 
deficit declined 84 percent in 1993 from the previous year. 
SARH noted that the 1992 trade deficit topped $761.47 million, 
while in 1993 the deficit reached $121.45 million. The report 
added that Mexico basically continues to sell raw coffee, fresh 
vegetables, and fruit, except for cantaloupe and watermelon, and 
is still purchasing soybeans, sorghum, and wheat. (Mexico City 
LA JORNADA in Spanish 6 May 94 p 57) 
  It has been reported that 68 of the 213 nonfinancial 
business 
enterprises on the Mexican Stock Exchange (BMV) registered net 
losses during the first three months of 1994. On the other 
hand, 79 consortiums reported their profits dropped by 23.2 
percent, while 66 enterprises registered increases. (Mexico 
City LA JORNADA in Spanish 6 May 94 pp 72, 58) 
  The depreciation of the peso and the increase in interest 
rates, particularly 28-day Treasury Notes, have prompted 
financial middlemen to record losses in their net earnings in 
the first three months of the year. At least eight trading 
companies reported losses, 10 percent of the customers from 154 
investment societies withdrew, and more than eight banks 
reported heavy losses. In addition, 60 companies in the BMV 
registered exchange losses worth more than 4.352 billion new 
pesos. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 9 May 94 p 6) 
  In view of the increasing debts of corporations and 
individuals, less financing from national banks, and the 
uncertainty prevailing in the economy with regard to the lack of 
growth, consumer prices continued to drop in the first three 
months of the year. According to reports from 17 businesses 
working with the BMV, their net sales amounted to 12.343 billion 
new pesos from January to March 1994. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO 
in Spanish 9 May 94 p 3A) 
  The federal and state governments have invested 
approximately 
179 million new pesos in Chiapas State to be used in emergency 
programs in the areas of electrification, potable water works, 
and productive programs. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 9 
May 94 p 3) 
  Juan Ramon Jimenez, an economist from the Technological 
Institute of Monterrey who is conducting a study on the 
concentration of wealth, has concluded that 60 percent of the 
revenue generated in the country is being earned by 10 percent 
of the population, while 10 percent of the overall annual income 
is being distributed among 60 percent of the population. 
Jimenez says this "gap between the rich and poor" is the result 
of the fact the Mexican economy is highly monopolized. For 
example, the value of the shares owned by eight companies in the 
BMV is equivalent to one-fourth of the GDP. (Mexico City LA 
JORNADA in Spanish 9 May 94 p 48) 
  On 9 May, the Bank of Mexico reported that Mexico registered 
an inflation rate of 0.5 percent during April, and that the 
annual inflation rate so far this year amounts to 2.31 percent, 
which is lower than the inflation rate for the same period in 
1993, which amounted to 3.27 percent. (Paris AFP in Spanish 
0045 GMT 10 May 94) 
  Given the weakness in the world fuel market, which has been 
generated by an excessive supply of petroleum products and the 
fall in international prices, Mexican petroleum exports declined 
at an annual rate of 16.6 percent in the first two months of 
1994. Overseas sales of crude, its by-products, and 
petrochemical products totaled $986.6 million in the first two 
months of the year. This represents 19.5 percent of the 
nation's total exports, without taking into account assembly 
plant exports in this same period. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in 
Spanish 2 May 94 p 3A) 
  During the first two months of the year, Mexican public 
sector exports, without taking into account assembly plants, 
only grew 11.9 percent over the same period last year when they 
registered a growth rate of 21.5 percent. Nevertheless, the 
exports by the Mexican private sector in this same period grew 
21.5 percent. Sales to various international markets totaled 
$5.58 billion, of which $3.70 billion was for semi-finished 
goods, $1.502 billion for consumer goods, and $484.8 million for 
capital goods. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 3 May 94 p 
21) 
  A Bank of Mexico report indicates that the nation's current 
accounts deficit has grown more than 700 percent during this 
administration. According to the report, the trade exchange of 
merchandise was one of the factors that influenced the increase 
the most, with imports outpacing exports. The current accounts 
balance in tourism registered a $605.2 million surplus, while 
revenues from travelers totalled $6.167 billion. (Mexico City 
UNOMASUNO in Spanish 3 May 94 p 16) 
  Factors affecting administration, customs, handling, and 
dredging work, as well as the increase in maritime traffic in 
local waters and a lack of infrastructure for port facilities, 
have resulted in a decrease in services to foreign trade since 
the implementation of NAFTA. Moreover, extended delays for 
ships in Mexican ports have created huge increases in operating 
costs, which are estimated to run as much as $5,000 a day for a 
ship in port. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 3 May 94 p 
24) 
  A Secretariat of Commerce and Industrial Development study 
indicates that Mexican sales to the United States increased 22.6 
percent over the first two months of the year "as a result of 
the implementation of NAFTA." The study also notes that the 
Mexican farming sector has a dynamic role in exports to the 
United States in terms of peeled citrus, dried melons, prepared 
potatoes, prepared tomatoes, dehydrated onions, nuts, canned 
vegetables and fruits, melons, watermelons, papayas, and 
sunflower seeds. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 3 May 94 
p 5) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

