<F P=100> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies IMF Seeks Further Cuts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Denies IMF Seeks Further Cuts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1105030094 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1811 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1105030094 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Buenos Aires, 10 May (NA) -- Finance Secretary 
Ricardo Gutierrez today denied reports indicating that the IMF 
would ask for a 10 percent cutback in the 1994 budget to be 
implemented. He emphasized that the fiscal surplus targets 
agreed upon for the first quarter "were surpassed." 
  Gutierrez noted that the surplus agreed upon with the IMF 
"totaled $640 million, and this target was surpassed by $60 
million as a $700 million surplus was achieved." 
  The finance secretary also believes that the IMF delegation 
will issue a favorable report on Argentine fiscal accounts. 
  Gutierrez added: "What we have done so far will not 
represent any problem or be deserving of any remarks from the 
IMF." 
  The finance secretary described as "entirely inaccurate" the 
reports on IMF concerns over the first quarter's fiscal results. 
He confirmed that this "is entirely mistaken information." 
  Gutierrez emphasized that "the first quarter's targets were 
surpassed." 
  The finance secretary said the IMF delegation would meet on 
12 or 13 May with the financial team. In addition to Gutierrez, 
the financial team also includes Economic Programming Secretary 
Juan Llach and Public Revenues Secretary Carlos Tacchi. 
  Gutierrez made these remarks after an economic team meeting 
at the Economy Ministry today. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

