<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Submits IMF Agreement To Open Discussion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Submits IMF Agreement To Open Discussion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1005232394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1752 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1005232394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Lima, 10 May (EFE) -- The Peruvian Government's 
decision to submit the 1994 economic program agreed upon between 
the government and the IMF to decision was backed today by all 
Peruvian entrepreneurial and political circles. 
  On 9 May, Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori indicated that 
his government would wait at least 10 days for experts to raise 
their proposals to improve the draft of the letter of intent 
before sending it to the IMF. 
  Economist Alejandro Indacochea, an Advanced Business School 
board member, noted that Fujimori's proposal was positive 
"because the publication of such documents had been considered 
taboo by former governments, which guarded them as if they were 
top state secrets." 
  Indacochea pointed out, however, that it would be impossible 
to voice an opinion on the letter of intent unless the annexes 
on the committed economic targets become known, and he asked the 
government to publish them as soon as possible. 
  The economist added that there is a point missing in the 
document "involving the overvaluation of soles against dollars 
and its negative impact on the trade deficit, which has not been 
overcome in four years and must be reversed." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

