<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Fujimori Leading Perez de Cuellar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Shows Fujimori Leading Perez de Cuellar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1105034494 Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 1 May 94 p A4 </F>
<F P=103> PY1105034494 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EXPRESO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In its latest survey, the Peruvian Public Opinion 
Poll (POP) shows that 64 percent of Peruvian voters believe 
Fujimori should seek reelection, while 63 percent of them 
approve of his performance as president. 
  If the 1995 presidential elections were held tomorrow, the 
incumbent president would obtain 49 percent of the votes, while 
Javier Perez de Cuellar would obtain 40 percent. The survey 
also shows that only 28 percent of those polled knew what Perez 
de Cuellar did for a living. 
  The POP survey focuses on the ideas voters have about 
Fujimori and Perez de Cuellar as presidential candidates for 
1995. They regard the incumbent chief executive as "a strong 
person who is better acquainted with Peruvian reality and who is 
better identified with the people." They believe the former UN 
secretary general has "greater international prestige." 

</TEXT>

